<:h1>Owle Schreame Awards</:h1>
<:p>The Owle Schreame Awards were 2014 theatrical awards honouring innovation in classical theatre. They were awarded by Brice Stratford and his Owle Schreame theatre company in 2014 to commemorate the 450th anniversary of Shakespeare's birth.</:p>
<:p>The award itself was an engraved glass skull, in reference to the famous graveyard scene in Shakespeare's "Hamlet". Thirteen were awarded, and the award speeches were published. The awards covered all forms of historical theatrical performance.</:p>
<:p>The winners were:</:p>
<:p>- Gods and Monsters Theatre, for "The Ring Cycle Plays"</:p>
<:p>- The Merely Players, for the "Merely Shakespeare" project</:p>
<:p>- Lazarus Theatre, for "The Tragedy of Mariam"</:p>
<:p>- Footfall, for "Lear's Daughters"</:p>
<:p>- Tacit Theatre, for "The Canterbury Tales"</:p>
<:p>- Scaffold Shakespeare, for the "Play out the Play" project</:p>
<:p>- The London Guildhall, for "Medea in the Amphitheatre"</:p>
<:p>- Factory Theatre, for "Hamlet" and "The Odyssey"</:p>
<:p>- Passion in Practice, for work in "Original Pronunciation"</:p>
<:p>- Rift, for the immersive "Macbeth"</:p>
<:p>- The Mummers Unconvention, for their work promoting "Mummers Plays"</:p>
<:p>- Edward's Boys, for "Gallathea"</:p>
<:p>- The Combat Veteran Players, for "Henry V"</:p>
